When a user exceeds their monthly query limit the API returns a 429 Too Many Requests response with rate-limit details. Example response in the docs:

{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

The API can also return rate-limit error objects such as:
- { "error": { "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED", "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds" } }
- or an INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS error for query-limit cases: { "error": { "code": "INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS", "message": "Need 5000 credits, have 5000" } }

When the monthly query limit is exceeded, the API returns a 429 Too Many Requests response with rate-limit details. Example response:

{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

Rate-limit headers are also included in responses.

When a user exceeds their monthly query limit the API returns a 429 Too Many Requests response with rate-limit details. Example response from the context:

{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

The usage fields mean:
- current: current usage this billing period
- max: maximum allowed queries (-1 = unlimited)
- exceeded: whether the limit has been reached
- reset_at: ISO 8601 timestamp when the monthly limit resets

Other related rate-limit responses shown in the context include:
- A 429-style error object: { "error": { "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED", "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds" } }
- An INSufficient-credits-style error for query limits: { "error": { "code": "INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS", "message": "Need 5000 credits, have 5000" } }

Rate limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset) are also included in responses.
